This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for borrow validation.

## Core concept

Borrow validation is a data-flow analysis over validated HIR. It checks whether accesses and inferred transfers remain safe across control flow.

## Beanstalk boundary

Borrow validation:

- reads HIR and semantic call summaries
- checks shared and exclusive access
- checks use after possible consumption
- treats collection and map aliases conservatively
- computes joins across branches and loops
- records function effects and read-only side tables

It does not rewrite HIR, compute source-visible lifetimes, choose allocation strategy or perform backend lowering.

GC remains the semantic baseline. Ownership-aware lowering may use stronger facts for optimisation without changing which programs are valid.

## Rewrite focus

Explain abstract states, roots, transfer functions, fixed points, conservative analysis and the difference between language safety and allocation optimisation.

Canonical details live in the compiler and memory authorities.
